I asked if I could mention them in my Review. See my 2 photos here of the ‚ÄúHow are we doing?‚Äù business size card here in the Photos section of this Review. < Text>
I wanted to take a few minutes and compliment the Go Wireless team.

My phone started acting up Friday evening.¬† The screen on my S10 (512 memory)¬† went black and only worked with a bright white line about 1 inch along the bottom and when connected to a charger.

I NEED a working phone and woke up on Saturday with the goal of going to bed with a replacement.¬† I use Verizon for their service and I drove over to the River to find that corporate store closed.¬† Fine I drove all the way to their second location in La Quinta only to be told I couldn't shop in store and they could text me a link.¬† Very frustrating as my phone wasn't working (I could dial out through the Bluetooth on my car)¬† While on hold for 10 minutes with Verizon, I drove over to gowireless off  Washington.¬† I also contemplated switching companies as the corporate solution was ridiculous.

I walked right in and was immediately greeted with how can I help you.¬† I spoke with Miguel and explained my dilemma and we picked out a phone.¬† Only to find out that store didn't have the model I wanted. I asked if the PS location did and he said yes and called Adrian and sent me that way.¬† I was planning to get my haircut right next door it was perfect.

Adrian was also very helpful and was about to sell me the phone we both thought I wanted when he noticed I had the 512 version and the one available was only 128.¬† We checked and saw I was already using 104 and I said I wanted the 256 version of the S21.¬† Well there was only 1 in the valley down in PD.¬† So Adrian called and spoke with Javier and made sure I could get it if I headed down there.

I did and Javier quickly transferred my data and sent me on my way with a new phone.¬† I really appreciated the way your team members were not focused on a commission or a sale and more focused on getting me the RIGHT phone.¬† Even Christian from the Washington store was very helpful, friendly and professional when I called and got your email.

Before this transaction I avoided the Go Wireless stores and headed straight to the corporate store.¬† Now I will only be visiting your establishment when I am in need of upgrading.

Great Job Gowireless<//Text>

< Review>
Just off the street headed towards Vista Point.
It's a great place for a walk by yourself or with a friend.
It stretches out pretty far.
It's about an hour loop around the trail
It can be hot at day so make sure to bring plenty of water.
The walk up the trail should be fairly easy for most</Review>

<username>Jeff Hubbs</username>< Review>
Nice trail. A bit warm but nice. Parts of the trail are quite narrow had to stop quite a bit to let others pass going the other way. That was ok. Definitely worth it to see the view. WOW trail is 1.83 miles with a 300 foot elevation gain. It is very steep then levels out a bit for the loop. It took 1 hour and 10 min. Wife kept having to stop. Not used to the temperature.</Review>

<user_name>nate stein< /user_name><date>1546021668398< /date>< text>
My favorite hike. Counted 16 big horns at one point hanging out snacking with us. Dead Indian canyon is just so fun once you get to the bouldering at the oasis. The wash was beautiful, but don't wear sandles as the sand and rocks will get stuck in your shoes. The big horns weren't scared of us either, we were about 5 feet from them. Be aware the trail closes Jan 1 to protect the big horns. Also, no dogs because they scare the big horns.</text>

<user_id>117799280761197186394</user_id>< user_name>
Darleen</user_name>
< date>
1547942589135</date>
< rating>
5< /rating>
<text>This is a lovely walk through rocky hillsides.  The trail begins with a sharp ascent via switchbacks on the north side of a small valley.  I happened to be there after the rains so everything was green and blossoming.   Once you reach the top things level out until you get to the split off for another trail.  Then there is a constant but gradual uphill climb.  The walk takes you through cactus gardens, beautiful rock formations,  and a former palm tree oasis (all the trees are dead).  Further on when you come to a live oasis you'll know that you are close to reaching the top of a plateau.   At that point you see spectacular views of the Coachella Valley below, and the San Jacinto Mountains above.  This is where I stopped to have lunch.  According to my fitbit I had walked about 4 miles.  The trail continues on for another 8 miles but I will have to tackle that on another day!  I highly recommend this hike in the spring when the wildflowers are abundant.   You won't be disappointed.< /text>< Pictures>
[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPnobhgy6SZKRkbR1H3gMBBSjaRek65jPevtVU_=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipO4cyB2OxY2mgJeneB83O4vWsOQ0JOeKSUUq7WX=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPFSWmo9YcqSq2Xq7l9jLubfxSfO4pimTTHiAeZ=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNACT-_0xBAazJ8tU11bGnMt_kH0SAESqP6Jtao=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]<//Pictures>

I requested a different beverage and let it go. I figured it was a pandemic thing.

<rating>2< /rating>< text>
First time here. Service was horrible. We weren't greeted. Stood around and finally sat down at sushi bar even though it needed to be cleaned. We waited and waited. I got up to get a menu. We weren't even offered drinks. We finally, asked for drinks. They didn't come. Had to ask again. A bus boy came and cleaned but didn't give us are utensils...  Chop sticks, napkins ...
Waitress finally acknowledged us. We were very patient for they had a large party and others and ONE waitress! I felt bad for her. It's not her fault.
Sushi bar chef was solo as well and swamped. He finally took our order after we remembered we had to fill the order chart out which I went searching for and found on bar! We ordered food came and it was FANTASTIC!  The good news!
Sushi chef was very pleasant.
But service sucked that night.
After the large group left I mentioned to waitress and cheft did someone call out sick? She was working hard. No, she was on her own her second week! The whole restaurant!
They locked the doors for it was closed and we were still eating. They cleaned around up around us. We sat for it seemed like forever to get the bill. We had to ask a few times. It was awkward.
Food was great. Service was lacking.</text>

I ordered shrimp vermicelli and the sauce was very bland no flavor. Also the shrimp were supposed to be grilled and they just tasted oily. I also ordered Shrimp spring rolls and the peanut sauce tasted like Formaldehyde!! It is the worst peanut sauce I have ever tasted. Spring rolls also came with a red sauce which I thought it would be the sweet and sour chili sauce that they typically come with and it was just straight chili. The third thing I ordered was eggplant and tofu which was SO oily. The vegetables and tofu were swimming in oil. Overall, I was extremely disappointed especially after having spent $60 for the 3 dishes. I don‚Äôt know how this restaurant got the google stars that that did.<//review>

< review>
Cozy place with friendly staff and good food. The portions are huge even with regular sized pho. There are options for vegetarian dishes. Try the freshly cut chilled coconut water. The food is authentic and tasty. It is crowded fairly and you may not get an easy parking in the complex. Take out is one option. Overall - good place next to a taco joint and Peruvian place.</review>

< Review>
Safe to say this is one of our favorite pho places. Always hits the spot and consistently friendly service. The round and brisket is definitely my choice especially since the meat is not too fatty and balances the dish well. Beware of the jalapeno pepper, those can be spicy from time to time. Only downside is finding parking when it gets busy especially during lunch. They have quite a few restaurants there and there's no easy in and out from that area. Go early or late to avoid this issue.<//Review>

<userid>111584109935424734670<//userid><user_name>Lynn Chayatanan<//user_name><date>1534797128563< /date>< rate>
3<//rate>
< review>
I'll start by saying the service here is top notch, especially for a Vietnamese restaurant. Two people were always watching if I happened to glance up, and I was served promptly and graciously. The food here is very palatable, and it arrive quickly and fresh to my table. My issue with this place is that the food does not taste like Vietnamese food to me. I was still craving grilled pork when I left, although the grilled pork I had here was not bad. There was fresh white onion slices and served on my place along with the veggies, but that was a first for me. Another variable was price. For a rice plate (grilled pork with imperial roll combo, $11.95 as of posting) and a drink (Vietnamese iced coffee, $4.50 as of posting) my total came to $17.93, leaving me to leave put an end evening tip, leaving me a whole $20 lighter when I left. Knowing I can get a similar meal for $3-4 cheaper in my neighborhood in SF and knowing I would leave with my flavor cravings satiated, I will most likely only return to try their pho. From the looks of orders from other tables, maybe that is what they do best. For my first experience, I would say excellent service, about 25% overpriced, and a rather different flavor combination than usual for their rice dishes. Being an avid Vietnamese food lover, I will return to try again.<//review>

< Text>
I cannot talk more highly of this place!  I love Pho quite a bit and heard nice things about Thai crepes so I had to give it a try.  Their menu is very concise with lots of options (which sounds contrary but trust me, they have it all).

Started with the sprint rolls and got the combo meal which includes a small bowl of Pho (which is a pretty big bowl) as well as a choice of 3 types of meat from a list of about 7 things and then extra stuff on the side.  All for like $14.95!  Great deal and I guarantee you will be taking food home for later.

They said in about 2 weeks (so around the start of April) they will be hiring someone to work the crepe station and our server claims they will offer savory and dessert crepes as well as bubble teas.  So we will be heading back very soon!

We got 2 apps, numerous sakas, 2 combo meals and it was a little over $50.< /Text>

< review>
If you are an experienced Pho 'Foodie', I would not recommend this location. The Pho broth tasted like there was some type of bullion cubes and or some type of instant broth powder added.

I also ordered the vermicelli with pork and egg rolls. The Noodles seems like they had been sitting in cold water before served to me and the pork was sour. The Egg rolls had that kind-of white layer like freezer burn on the outside and the meat-mix inside was mushy and also sour.

To top it off, I wasn't even going to complain, I took a couple of bites and actually left ALL my food. But then she asked was everything okay. I offered to pay after leaving an entire meal, I gave her some brief feedback and she still charged me. LOL!!! She acted concerned but not concerned enough to make it right. I'm not trying to get something for free.

Bad first experience. I personally will not attempt to try there again. Like I said, experienced Pho-eaters beware. If you havent been to too many good eats, maybe you wont know the difference.

Bad first experience.</review>

<userid>105134430132682884788<//userid><name>Kyle Samuelson< /name>< date>
1537820439930< /date>
<rate>5</rate>< review>
Very well kept restaurant overall.
Clean on the outside, clean on the inside, kitchen looks clean and well maintained.

All tables bolted to the ground, very sturdy, no wobbly tables. New granite counter tops, very clean. Everything organized, and topped off. Feels very welcoming.

Seems like authentic Mexican food, non-Americanized. Clients are mostly Spanish speaking Mexicans.

Menu with prices painted onto wall, looks nice. Good prices.

Very simple restaurant with a very good execution.<//review>

< Review>
Wife and I were craving Mexican after a pregnancy check-in at Orange Coast Memorial. Found this in a Google Maps search and decided to give it a try. Wife ordered carnitas burrito and I went with an al pastor quesadilla. Both were fresh, made to order, tasted great, and were exactly what we were looking for. < Review>
Magnificent tacos with the authentic touch of Mexico City.
Here you can find on Taco Tuesday, all of them at only .95 cents and believe me that they offer a variety, from lengua (tongue) to cabeza ( beef cheek) to sesos (brains) to regular ones, like carnitas, asada and Al pastor.
Plus if you want something else, like quesadillas or combo plates you can have them as well.
So if visiting or in Orange County, try them, you won't be dissapointed at all!!!!< /Review>

I have NEVER had a dental experience as positive as the one i had this morning! I broke a tooth a while back but had no pain so i just letf it alone. Over the weekend i started getting pains so bad that i would start to black out. Being new to the area, i went online and found Dr. Chen at Solano Dental Group in Fairfield.  He had nearly 300 fantastic reviews,  every single review!
I called, got an appointment, got dressed and went there. Everyone was so kind. Dr. Chen had me out of pain literally within minutes! I felt 100% confident in him & his assistant. Still, the cost of the work i had done & still needed to get done was far less than other dentists i had gotten estimates for. The office manager was super nice and she gave me info on an outside private dental plan called "Gold Dental Plan". I signed up at home and it saved me so much money!! I am ready to go next week & have Dr. Chen finish my root canal and put on a permanent crown (all in one appointment too!).

<pics>None< /pics><gmap_id>0x80851426f3de80cb:0x286afed680a6d6ff< /gmap_id><Response>None<//Response><user_name>Brad Rowland<//user_name>< Text>
I am a patient of Dr Chen.  During my exam Dr Chen suggest I ask my physician to test for sleep apnea.  I took his advice and got tested at my healthcare provider.  I was diagnosed with moderate sleep apnea.  I am now using  CPAP (Continuous Positive Airway Pressure) which is a machine that has improved my sleep and reduced my sleep apnea down to positive levels.  If you are having problems with snoring and feeling tired please talk to your health care provider.  They have a simple test to determine if you have this condition.  Sleep apnea can be a serious condition if not treated.  Long term sleep apnea can contribute to a high blood pressure, daytime fatigue, type 2 diabetes, heart problems and obesity.  If it was not for Dr Chen suggesting I get tested it could have lead to developing one or more of these complications.
Thank you
Dr Chen<//Text>

Take my word for it and go here for your dental needs!

I can put my word in for how professional Dr. Tsang was in taking care of my dental needs. Take a peek at the pictures below AND tell me that isn't amazing! Throughout my case, he was able to communicate my dental needs, costs, and operations in a professional manner, look for ways to save me money through insurance, and have patience for my tedious dental case. He is also very well-spoken, which I noticed off the first bat of meeting him. This was nothing like my last dentist!

Not to mention, his staff, from the front desk workers to the dental assistants, surgeons, and the lab staff in Pinole. Shoutout to y'all! I've had chances to interact with a lot of the staff and I can say, without a doubt, they are a culturally diverse group that really CARES about your dental needs.

For my dental case pictures on the bottom, I had a dental crown procedure done on my front four teeth. <Time>1597964623251< /Time>< rating>
5</rating>
<Review>First visit with Dr. Tsang and staff. From my first phone call to Crystal explaining why I was looking for a new dentist, to the efficiency of new patients forms emailed (less direct contact during COVID-19), to discussions of wether or not I should get prior records to my first visit, I could not have felt more positive about being a person that was cared for and not a faceless number. Welcoming, professional and compassionate at every encounter. A day before my appointment I was emailed a Covid questionnaire, and my temperature was taken upon arrival. Staff wearing masks and face shields. A very efficient wearing masks and face shields. A very efficiency run practice. Crystal who answered the phone also did my x-rays, the doctor also took photos of my teeth, did a full examination, went over my hot spots with suggestions and treatment plans, and he did my cleaning. The dental assistant was in there assisting with water and suction while the doctor used the ultrasound to clean, picks for under the gums and polished. Quick, painless (always checked to see if I was comfortable and could raise my hand to indicate sensitivity) and professional. Dr. Tsang and I had a frank discussion about my gums and overall teeth health and I left with a plan, follow up visit and equipment to better care for my oral health. Your parting gift bag does not include a .50 generic toothbrush and floss, but a spin brush for better gum health, floss and toothpaste. He also suggested using an air floss which I purchased from him for less than Target prices (I checked).
Dr. Tsang and his office are true professionals who care for your health and treat you as a person and not a wallet. Their cash client discounts are significant and much better than my prior who only gave me 10% discount. I would highly recommend him to anyone.

Everyone is calm, helpful, and very knowledgeable in their areas of expertise. Going to a dentist doesn't have to be a traumatic experience, and Dr. Tsang demonstrates that every time I visit.

I hate seeing a dentist. Just the sound of drills haunts me till this day. Ive been in search of a new dentist since my old one moved away. So I made an appointment with Dr. Tsangs office. I spoke to Elsa. She is a really nice and helpful lady. That's probably one of the nicest and most helpful ladies in a dentist office. EVER! < text>
They have the best ice-cream in town. I have been buying since I am in high school, that is in 95. I especially love their Black Sesame, Green Tea, Espresso & Dutch chocolate. I recently introduced to my son, he loves the Cookie & Cream and Real Vanilla. They have plenty of flavors to choose from, don't think you will go wrong with any. After so many years, they only take cash, so remember to bring some when you go. If ice cream is not your cup of tea, they do have sherbet and yogurt. Whenever you are in the area, remember to stop by and treat yourself to a yummy sweet dessert.<//text>

<review>A good variety of flavors. They let you sample three flavors. I ended up with the coffee cookie one. Overall good ice cream. Less creamy consistency and more smooth so it won't melt as fast. The setting is brightly lit with old-timey decor. Three cones with three single scoops came out to $9.75. To be honest Thrifty Rite Aid ice cream is just as good and you get bigger scoops. <Review>I wanted to see if the ice cream lived up to the hype and I have to say that I came away disappointed. The ice cream itself is fairly creamy and you can tell that its made with love, but there's just no flavor. I ordered cookie dough and nutella expecting a decadent delight, but it tasted very bland. <date>1591576668433<//date><Rate>3</Rate>< review>
Went with my girlfriend and we got 6 scoops between us. She got the short end of the stick, she had the fresh peach which tasted like it was mixed with nail polish remover, the taro which tasted nothing like taro but was a really good coconut flavor, and the cherry vanilla which was actually very good. <user_id>109684050072323676955<//user_id><user_name>Laura Tatiana Moreno< /user_name>< date>
1551675227060< /date>
<Rating>1</Rating>< review>
I must say I was very excited about trying this ice cream place, based on reviews and word of mouth. However, I was highly disappointed, the ice-cream was tasteless, the waffle cones are not freshly made, the scoops are tiny and they don't take credit cards. I had the Taro and my husband the pistachio, and we both couldn't believe how over-rated this place is. We visit many ice-cream shops, so once you try good creamy ice cream you know what's good, and this place is far from it. The good thing is, that even though it was busy, the staff is pretty good in getting people in and out, so no complaints there. But for the price and taste you rather go to a local store and get some Tillamook ice cream and pre-packaged waffle cones. Or just drive to Creamistry. (for some reason my husband's ice cream was much smaller than mine)< /review>

<Time>1511756330477<//Time><rate>4</rate><text>An old fashioned ice cream shop in the L.A. area. They make their own ice cream on the premises. Staff are friendly and competent. < Review>
One of the nicest icecream places I've been to in LA! Fosselman's is a small icecream shop in Alhambra and it's maintained by the family who started it and they have only one icecream parlour. < text>
Love going to this place.  They just did a remodel of the place, they are celebrating 100 years in the business.  They have seasonal flavors and they are constantly making new flavors to meet the needs of the growing diversity in the area.  What I mean is you can find horchata, green tea, or Guinness, if you want to be adventurous or if you just want good old fashioned vanilla they have that too.  They have a variety of sorbets on the menu and just added soft serve as well.  You have many choices here from sundaes to just a scoop of ice cream, whatever you fancy they have.    I particularly enjoy their fruit flavors they are quite refreshing.<//text>

This place used to be great. Friendly employees who were eager to help. However, the last several times I came in, there wasn't a single smile from behind the counter and I felt rushed trying to decide which flavor to get. I always get my mint and chip in a cake cone and in the past, the staff always managed to packed my ice cream into the cone so the ice cream was there until the last bite. The last several times, I ended up with an empty cone that was basically only there to hold my ice cream. I've been coming to this place for a long time and it's very sad to see this place going down the drain because they don't train their employees.<//text>

<name>Jon Marshall<//name>< Text>
A fantastic old-school ice cream joint with rich and savory flavors to explore.  Take what you know about ice-cream and elevate it a bit.  Stuff is GOOD here.  The place isn't huge - has a few seats inside and bit on the outside, but it's all irrelevant when you're coming to cool down the taste buds with some ice creamy goodness.  I won't get into favorite flavors - we each have our own, but sample a few and narrow down if you must.
Aside from the main draw of taste satisfaction, the historic aspect of the long-time running venue could appeal to some.  There are even nostalgic trinkets and what-not strewn about the shelves and such.  Maybe not a blatant walk back in time, but pretty close (just ignore the traffic outside).<//Text>

< Review>
I have been treating myself to Fosselman's ice cream since I was about 16, after I got my driver's license and could drive there. I am now 57 and still treat myself to Fosselman's every now and then. I've taken scores of people there and all agree, it is one of the best ice cream parlors, period. As my nephew once said, it is like biting into a cloud. Creamy, smooth, sweet, light, flavor packed. Absolutely amazing. On par with Marianne's in Santa Cruz!< /Review>

< Text>
The ice cream is pretty good. But not amazing.
The reason for the stars is for their AMAZING SORBETS! This is such a relief since the little princess is allergic to all things milk. We are constantly disappointed that there is seldom any quality desserts for her at most places.
This place has 6-8 homemade,  fresh, and truly dairy free Sorbets!
Yum Test approved!

Cash only
Limited seats
Gets crowded
No mixing of scoops. ...1 scoop, 1 flavor.
No toppings!  You will get charged for a Sundae if you want any toppings at all.
$2.95 for 1 scoop.

3.5 Stars. ...round up to 4.<//Text>

Very good, creamy ice cream. But the place takes cash only, which in this day and age is a real inconvenience to customers when trying to buy more than just an ice cream cone. Fosselman's is something of an institution in Alhambra and San Gabriel Valley. The place isn't fancy, but sort of 1960s funky ( not hippie funky, but suburban funky) but the ice cream is very good. I was, however, disappointed with it's version mocha almond fudge--not much flavor, very little fudge ribboning, and very few almonds.< /review>

<Text>Fosselman is a top-notch quality ice cream shop that has been around since 1916. The taro is pretty good, so I had a scoop of it once again and it tasted as good as it did 4 years ago when I first stumbled upon this shop in Alhambra. If I can't make it out to Alhambra, Little Tokyo has a shop that sells Fosselman ice cream, but doesn't have the variety and volume this one has. I would buy a tub of ice cream for $8.95... my friend commented that if we bought a different flavor ice cream tub every week, we might be able to try all the flavors in a little more than a year. Definitely worth visiting if you're in the area.</Text>< Pics>

<Date>1425968612269<//Date><Rate>3<//Rate><Text>I haven't been here for a long time so I was looking forward to tasting their ice cream again. Parking lot is small but you can park on the streets. Outside the storefront people were eating their ice cream.  As I walked in, I saw tables, chairs, candies, ready packaged ice cream, and a display case of decorative ice cream treats. We got in line and waited for our turn.  The lady who helped us was not pleasant. Final decision, we ordered one scoop of Mango Sorbet with a sugar cone, Cookies and Cream Ice Cream with a sugar cone and Strawberry Sorbet in a cup.

~Dessert~
The Strawberry Sorbet was good. It was creamy with strawberry pieces.  I tasted the Mango Sorbet, it's made with Indian Mangos; it was smooth. Unfortunately, the Cookies and Cream was not flavorful.  The Oreo Cookies didn't taste fresh and it had an odd flavor.  I would order the Strawberry Sorbet again!

~Customer Service~
I was disappointed because the lady who assisted us was not friendly and she seemed annoyed; I felt rushed.

~Rating~
The ice cream was not the greatest but it wasn't awful either.  The service was a big turn off. I'm not sure if I would come back again.

~Notes~
~Cash Only
~The lady that worked there said we could only sample three ice creams per person
~Single Scoop: $3.50 / Double Scoop: $4.90 / Triple Scoops: $5.75< /Text>< Pics>

<text>There's not much to say as the thousands of reviews speak for itself.

This is a gem in the SGV area and many 626 locals will say this is the best ice cream anywhere. I have to say I've never been disappointed with any of their flavors and can kill numerous scoops in just minutes.

Expect a decent line if you're here on weekends.
Green tea, Thai tea, taro, black sesame and horchata are all must have flavors! It's so damn rich in heavenly goodness that your mouth waters just by looking at it.

I am sure if this place were to expand in Silverlake/Eagle Rock, they'd get all the hipsters getting this ice cream all day errday.</text>< pics>

<Review>Yay finally made an excuse to visit a friend so I could try this place!!

Wish it wasnt so freezing outside so I could enjoy the ice cream more (plus I was sick). Cute lil ice cream parlor with so many unique ice cream flavors!

I got:
Taro - rich sweet potato flavor, I could see why some people aren't that fond of this flavor. I enjoyed it because I grew up eating taro.

Lychee - one of my favorite fruit. Was expecting it more to taste like sorbet. It was very creamy and the lychee flavor was there. I liked it but I don't think I'll be craving for it anytime soon. Maybe I would have tasted the sweetness more if i ate the lychee before the taro...

I'm def coming back when it's not so cold outside! I want to try their other flavors!!!< /Review><gmapID>0x80c2c51da2544149:0x6b7e703dba4dd8b8< /gmapID><date>1451297412467< /date>< UserId.>

<user_name>Jackson Yang<//user_name><date>1432248705887< /date><Rating>5</Rating><Review>Been a local to Alhambra for pretty much all of my life. Always thought it was just some really awesome ice cream store that I can walk to! Never really thought too much of Fosselman's until I saw it on the Food Network's Unwrapped. Who knew the little ice cream parlor so renown!

It seems like the rest of Alhambra has changed, but Fosselman's seems to have locked itself in a time capsule. The place probably looks exactly how it looked like when it first opened back in the 1920s? I think about this place when people make fat kid jokes, because its full of ice cream, candies, and everything sweet(it seems like).

These days, a scoop of real ice cream can cost anywhere from $3-5 bucks! But not over here, a hefty scoop of ice cream is only $2.50. My favorites are cookies N cream, chocolate chip cookie dough, and dolce de leche.

I've recently tried their ice lemonade, its $2. On a hot sunny day in So Cal, nothing feels more refreshing than a cup of that frothy ice cold lemonade! Heres a Tip, use a spoon! If you use the straw, you are gonna get nothin' but the sweet stuff. And left with lemon flavored frost!

If the small parking lot is full, do not fear! Its perfectly fine to park on the street! You won't feel so guilty afterwards.... when you have walked a few extra steps. =]</Review>< pictures>
None</pictures>

<review>(Translated by Google) Ice cream and ice cream cones are commonly referred to as ice cream in mainland China, ice cream in Hong Kong and Macau, and ice cream and cones in Singapore. Ice cream, ice cream, and ice cream are common but different[1] [2], collectively referred to as "ice cream, ice cream, ice cream, cones", is a kind of frozen dessert, usually made from fresh cream or dairy products such as cream, and mixed with fruits or other ingredients and spices. Most ice creams contain sugar, but some use other sweeteners. Sometimes in addition to natural ingredients, artificial flavors or food colorings are also added in the manufacturing process. The mixed raw materials will be stirred while cooling down to mix in air and prevent ice crystals from forming. The finished product will be in a semi-solidified state with a smooth surface, and can be shaped or scooped with a spoon.

Industrial-made ice cream is generally filled with mixed ice cream liquid into a mold placed in an ice-salt mixture. The ice-salt mixture will absorb a lot of heat in the process of supercooling and melting, which can make the ice cream freeze quickly. According to the "Federal Food Act of the United States", the milk fat content in ice cream is at least 10% by weight.

This ice cream is really delicious, and he promotes his wine series.
